cs|2|fp|3|at|^-
{        Constructive Auctions after a 1NT Opening Bid       }
^-|FP||at|^b@2^Y@3Constructive auctions after a 1NT opener are very straightforward. These auctions very much 
illustrate the "responder is Captain" principle which we discussed in the last lesson. As opener, you should open 1NT if at all possible. This includes opening 1NT without stoppers in some suits and with a 5-card major. 1NT is a very descriptive bid--it shows 15-17 HCP and only 3 possible hand shapes (4-4-3-2, 5-3-3-2, and 4-3-3-3). |
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT|

^-{ Responder Hand Categories }
^-|AT|^b@2^Y@3
In all of these lessons, I will assume the reader uses basic hand evaluation techniques. That is, he or she uses the standard 4-3-2-1 method for counting HCP and makes small adjustments for either shortness or length. I now teach, and prefer, the more accurate Bergen methodology, but because it is not familiar to everyone, I will not use it in these lessons.

|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT|As responder, hands fall into one of 3 categories--|CP|8|FP|2|AT|MINIMUM, MEDIUM, or MAXIMUM. |FP||CP||AT|The point ranges are slightly different than the ranges we discussed earlier.  The  point ranges are:|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


CP|8|FP|2|AT|

  ^cMinimum |FP||CP||AT|^f- no more than 7 points; game is not possible;|CP|8|FP|2|AT|
  ^CMedium |FP||CP||AT|^f- 8-9 points; game is possible if opener has a maximum NT (defined below);|CP|8|FP|2|AT|
  ^CMaximum |FP||CP||AT|^f- 10 or more points; you must bid game.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|
    
When responder has a medium hand, opener is invited to bid game with maximum NT hand. A hand is considered maximum NT if it meets any of the following criteria:
^C* Any hand with 17 HCP
^C* Any hand with 16 HCP and a fit with responder's major suit
^C* Any hand with 16 HCP and a 5-card suit
^C* Any hand with 16 HCP, not 4-3-3-3 distribution, and at least two 10s or 9s.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT|
  
Now that you understand how to determine whether or not to bid game, the rest of the lesson will focus on how to determine whether the best contract is NT, hearts, or spades.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BMovie Maker: ^*N|cp||at|Note that some partnerships open a hand 1NT with two doubletons--with certain requirements.|
