^-{    The Jacoby Transfer Convention    }
|FP|2|cp|8|AT|Jacoby Transfers|CP||FP||AT| were devised to allow the 1NT opener to play the hand.
This is often advantageous, because it is more likely that the defense will give away a trick on  opening lead
if the strong hand (the 1NT opener) plays the last card at trick 1.
In fact, when the strong hand is concealed, you may take more than one additional trick
because the defense has to guess more.|
PG| ***** 88 ***** |


AT|

As responder, you should use Jacoby Transfers under the following circumstances:|
PG| ***** 89 ***** |


AT|
{ If you have a 6-card or longer major (even with 4 cards in the other major), even if you have a minimum hand. } |
PG| ***** 90 ***** |


AT| 
{ If you have a 5-card major and a minimum hand (even if you also have a 4-card major). }|
PG| ***** 91 ***** |


AT|
{ If you have a medium or maximum hand, a 5-card major and not precisely 4 cards in the other major
(as described earlier, you should use Stayman with a non-minimum and 5-4 in the majors). }|
PG| ***** 92 ***** |


AT|
{ Note: with 5-5 in the majors, you should use Jacoby Transfer. }|
PG| ***** 93 ***** |


AT|
{ And finally, if your hand qualifies, you should transfer even if you have very few points 
(even with 0 HCP!). It is always easier to play in a suit than in NT, particularly when responder is weak. }
^-|
