qx|B07, Garbage Stayman|cs|1|cp|2|fp|1|HT|b|at|
^-{ Constructive Auctions after a NT Opening Bid }

{          Garbage Stayman          }
^-|HT|g|cp||FP||at|^b@2^z@3In general, it is usually easier to play in a suit than NT. This is particularly true when responder has a weak hand. Garbage Stayman was invented to allow the contract to be played in a suit at the 2 level when responder has a very weak hand (usually 4 or fewer points).|
PG| ***** 274 ***** |


HT|j|AT|

There are 2 variations:
* Classic Garbage Stayman
* Major Suit Garbage Stayman|
PG| ***** 275 ***** |


HT|j|AT|

There are 2 variations:
* Classic Garbage Stayman
* Major Suit Garbage Stayman

Classic Garbage Stayman works as follows. Responder has a weak hand with at least 4 diamonds and at least 3 cards in each major. Over 1N, responder bids 2C. No matter what opener bids, responder passes. Therefore, the final contract will be either 2D, 2H, or 2S.|
PG| ***** 276 ***** |


HT|j|AT|

There are 2 variations:
* Classic Garbage Stayman
* Major Suit Garbage Stayman

Classic Garbage Stayman works as follows. Responder has a weak hand with at least 4 diamonds and at least 3 cards in each major. Over 1N, responder bids 2C. No matter what opener bids, responder passes. Therefore, the final contract will be either 2D, 2H, or 2S.

Major Suit Garbage Stayman works as follows. Responder has a weak hand with at least 4-4 in the majors. Over 1N, responder bids 2C. If opener bids 2H or 2S, responder has an easy pass, and is playing in a 4-4 fit. If opener bids 2D, then responder bids 2H. This tells opener that responder wants to play in either 2H or 2S. Opener passes with better hearts, and corrects to 2S with better spades. The final contract is often a 7-card major suit fit (since the NT opener cannot have a doubleton in both hearts and spades), but this is usually better than playing 1N with a weak dummy.|
PG| ***** 277 ***** |


HT|j|AT|

There are 2 variations:
* Classic Garbage Stayman
* Major Suit Garbage Stayman

Classic Garbage Stayman works as follows. Responder has a weak hand with at least 4 diamonds and at least 3 cards in each major. Over 1N, responder bids 2C. No matter what opener bids, responder passes. Therefore, the final contract will be either 2D, 2H, or 2S.

Major Suit Garbage Stayman works as follows. Responder has a weak hand with at least 4-4 in the majors. Over 1N, responder bids 2C. If opener bids 2H or 2S, responder has an easy pass, and is playing in a 4-4 fit. If opener bids 2D, then responder bids 2H. This tells opener that responder wants to play in either 2H or 2S. Opener passes with better hearts, and corrects to 2S with better spades. The final contract is often a 7-card major suit fit (since the NT opener cannot have a doubleton in both hearts and spades), but this is usually better than playing 1N with a weak dummy.

You can play both Classic and Major Suit Garbage Stayman simultaneously.
